inishing 2nd in their Champions League group will still sting them, they are carrying a bit of good form into the Christmas period now.</p><p>Antonio Conte looks to have tried to bolster his defence in recent weeks too, as their 1-0 win against Southampton at the weekend illustrates. They built their title winning campaign on their solid back line, but it’s faltered far too many times this season and it looks like Conte has finally addressed the situation now.</p><p>This is especially true on home soil, where they have kept a clean sheet in three of their last five matches in all competitions and won four of them. There are expected to be some changes to the lineup for this match though, at least if their last round fixture against Everton is anything to go by.</p><p>Willy Caballero could start between the sticks with Antonio Rudiger returning, but other than that their defensive setup could remain untouched. Besides that we could see Kenedy, Ampadu, Musonda, and Batshuayi brought in, but none of them should have an impact in the defensive aspect.</p><p>Bournemouth, on the other hand, are likely to be playing a full strength squad as they hunt for some unlikely silverware this season. Eddie Howe could opt for some changes though, especially after seeing his side hammered 4-0 at home to Liverpool on Sunday.</p><p>The Cherries are now winless in six matches in all competitions and find themselves struggling a bit, although away from home they tend to be a little tighter at the back. They only conceded one at Manchester United last week and limited Spurs to one as well. Their lack of scoring ability is an issue though, and it has resulted in four of their last six away games seeing fewer than three goals.</p><p>Chelsea have only seen one of their last five at home end with three or more goals as well, but despite this the bookies are expecting a goalfest. This leaves value out there for us, and backing Under 2.5 Goals at this price is fantastic value, along with a tigh