w they turn their attention to another piece of silverware, with the FA Cup 3rd Round draw pitting them against Championship promotion hopefuls Derby on Friday evening. It’s by no means the easiest entrance into the FA Cup, but Jose Mourinho will at least be pleased it’s on home soil.</p><p>Mourinho fielded quite a strong team in this round last season, and whilst they are suffering some injury problems at the moment we aren’t expecting too much in the way of rotation. All but the smallest amount of hope of catching Manchester City in the Premier League has disappeared, and whilst the Champions League is still very much in the frame, Mourinho will know that this is his best chance of silverware this season.</p><p>Derby won’t be pushovers though. The visitors drew at home to Sheffield United on Monday to make it seven matches unbeaten in all competitions, and the five wins during this period puts them 2nd in the Championship behind Wolves.</p><p>Away from home they are unbeaten since September and have scored in 13 of their 15 competitive matches this season, and whilst a victory at Old Trafford may seem far fetched, the in form attack will be fairly confident of getting on the scoresheet.</p><p>Manchester United have only lost one home match this season, but despite their defensive stability at the start of the campaign, that air of impenetrability has started to slip recently. Injuries have played their part, but Manchester United have conceded in three of their last five at home now and shipped two against Burnley on Boxing Day. This makes these odds fantastic value for Both Teams to Score, so we’re backing that as our main prediction.</p><p>The last few years have seen The Red Devils start strongly in the FA Cup though, and at home you would expect them to get a win. Considering nine of Derby’s away games this season have seen at least three goals, backing a Manchester United Win and Over 2.5 Goals alongside a 2-1 correct score predictions looks good value.</p><d